üõ°Ô∏è SECTION E ‚Äî MOBILE MONEY FRAUD (ORANGE MONEY & AFRICELL MONEY)

(Note: The following information explains general fraud patterns, not accusations against any specific company.)

Q62: What is mobile money fraud?

A:
Mobile money fraud occurs when criminals trick users into sending money, sharing PINs, revealing OTP codes, or approving transactions they did not authorize.

Q63: What are common mobile money scams in Sierra Leone?

A:
Common scams include:

Fraudsters calling and pretending to be ‚Äúcustomer care‚Äù

Messages claiming ‚Äúyour account has a problem‚Äù

Fake prize-winning SMS asking for fees

Attempts to steal PINs and OTP codes

Fake reversal requests asking users to return money they never received

SIM swap fraud

Q64: Do Orange and Africell agents ever ask for your PIN?

A:
No.
No mobile money agent or company representative will ever ask for your PIN, OTP, or private code.
Anyone requesting such information is attempting fraud.

Q65: What should you do if you receive a suspicious mobile money message?

A:

Do NOT respond

Do NOT click any links

Do NOT share your PIN or code

Call the official customer care number listed on the company website or SIM toolkit

Report it to GOVCHATBOT or to the police

Q66: What is SIM swap fraud?

A:
SIM swap fraud happens when someone tricks or bribes an agent to issue a duplicate SIM card of your number. Once they gain control of your SIM, they can access your mobile money, calls, SMS, and accounts linked to your phone number.

Q67: How can you prevent SIM swap fraud?

A:

Use strong PINs

Never share personal details

Monitor unusual phone behavior

Visit only official service centers for SIM issues

Register your SIM with accurate personal information

Q68: What should I do if money is withdrawn from my account without approval?

A:
You should immediately:

Call the official mobile money helpline

Freeze or lock your account (if supported)

Report the incident to the police

Document all transactions for investigation
Also report through GOVCHATBOT for guidance.

üõ°Ô∏è SECTION F ‚Äî PROTECTING YOURSELF FROM DIGITAL FRAUD
Q69: What is the best way to stay safe from digital scams?

A:

Verify all information

Keep your PIN and OTP private

Avoid untrusted links

Use official channels for payments

Beware of offers that sound ‚Äútoo good to be true‚Äù

Confirm any financial request through a phone call or physical visit

Enable two-factor authentication where possible

Q70: What should citizens do if they fall victim to a scam?

A:
They should gather evidence (screenshots, numbers, messages), report immediately to the police, contact their mobile money provider, and submit the incident to GOVCHATBOT for further guidance.

Q71: What role does the government play in fighting scams and misinformation?

A:
The government provides legal frameworks, public awareness campaigns, cybersecurity institutions, and cooperation with telecoms, financial institutions, and international partners to protect citizens and strengthen digital security.

